ew archival research, Green questions the conventional view of international economic history as a series of cyclical transitions among hegemonic powers. Instead, he explores the longstanding interactive role of private and public financial institutions in Britain and the United States-most notably the close links between their financial markets, central banks, and monetary and fiscal policies. He shows that America's unparalleled post-WWII financial power was facilitated, and in important ways constrained, by British capitalism, as the United States often had to work with and through British politicians, officials, and bankers to achieve its vision of a liberal economic order. Transatlantic integration and competition spurred the rise of the financial sector, an increased reliance on debt, a global easing of regulation, the ascendance of monetarism, and the transition to neoliberalism.From the gold standard to the recent global financial crisis and beyond, The Political Economy of the Special Relationship recasts the history of global finance through the prism of Anglo-American development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEconomic historyy1945-. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspectsxHistory. 0aInternational financexHistoryy20th century. 0aInternational finance. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aAmerican dollar.  aAmerican politics.  aAnglo-American financial development.  aBank of England.  aBanking Acts of 1933.  aBarry Eichengreen.  aBretton Woods.  aBrexit.  aBritish Bankers' Association.  aBritish politics.  aCapital Rules: The Construction of Global Finance.  aCity of London.  aEric Helleiner.  aEurodollar markets.  aFederal Reserve Board.  aGlass-Steagall.  aGlobalizing Capital: A History of the International Monetary System.  aJohn Maynard Keynes.  